🔹 2. Where does AHB fit?
AHB = Advanced High-performance Bus
Think of AMBA like a hierarchy:

Bus Type	Purpose
APB	Low-speed peripherals (UART, GPIO)
AHB	High-speed system bus
AXI	Modern high-performance interconnect

So AHB was designed for:
CPU ↔ memory
DMA ↔ memory
High bandwidth transfers

🔄 2. Support multiple masters
CPU
DMA
Debug unit
AHB introduced:
Arbitration
Shared bus access

🧠 4. Simpler than modern protocols
Compared to AXI:
Less complexity
Easier to implement
Lower area/power

🔹 4. Why NOT AXI (at that time)?
👉 AXI didn’t exist yet
AHB came first. Later, ARM introduced AXI when requirements evolved.


🔹 5. Then why AXI replaced AHB?
As systems got more complex:
🚫 Limitations of AHB
Single shared bus → contention
No true parallel transactions
Blocking nature (one transfer at a time)
Not scalable for many masters


✅ AXI improvements
Multiple independent channels (read/write)
Out-of-order transactions
Multiple outstanding requests
Better for multicore + high bandwidth
👉 That’s why AXI dominates modern SoCs.

🔹 6. Where AHB is still used today
Even now, AHB is not dead:
Mid-level interconnects
Simpler SoCs
Microcontroller-class designs
